Ford Go Bike Data Exploration¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

We will use Ford Go Bike data set from https://www.fordgobike.com/system-data consists of trips that taken by service's members on February 2019.

Data Content:

    1. information about trip service's members, type, age and gender. 
    2. information about stations,id ,name.
    3. information about trip starting date, ending date and duration of trips in seconds.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 trips in the dataset with 8 features (duration_minutes, user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip, member_age, startDate,startHour, and startDay). duration_minutes and member_age variables are numeric , but the variables user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip, startDate,startHour, and startDay are categorical.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features that strengthened the trip duration time.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that All previous mentioned variables will have effects on the the trip duration time.

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: trip duration time.

binsize = 1
bins = np.arange(0, fordBike['duration_minutes'].max()+binsize, binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = fordBike, x = 'duration_minutes', bins = bins)
plt.title('Distribution of Trip Durations')
plt.xlabel('Duration (minutes)')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')
plt.xlim(0, 50)#Remove outliers 
plt.axvline(x= fordBike.duration_minutes.mode().tolist(), color='r', lw=1)
plt.axvline(fordBike.duration_minutes.mean(), color='k', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)

min_ylim, max_ylim = plt.ylim()
plt.text(fordBike.duration_minutes.mean()*1.1, max_ylim*0.9, 'Mean: {:.2f}'.format(fordBike.duration_minutes.mean()))
plt.show()

def hist2dgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating heat maps with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    bins_x = np.arange(0, 60+binsize, binsize)
    bins_y = np.arange(18, 100+binsize, binsize)
    plt.hist2d(x, y, bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5)
